History 101    | Department of History | New York University                                  NEW YORK UNIVERSITY     ARTS AND SCIENCE     COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE     GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE             Department of History     Arts & Science                      Back to Home       History 101   There has recently been a change in the curriculum: History 101 has been reformed in response to student feedback! Former incarnations of the course as it has been previously taught, the history workshop (V57.0900) and Historical Studies: Theories & Practice (HIST-UA 101), have been replaced with History 101: Historical Interpretation .  History 101, “Historical Interpretation,” introduces majors to the core skills, methods, and approaches of the discipline. Beginning from Fall 2014, it now teaches this key disciplinary content, such as reading primary sources and analyzing historical arguments, through a series of case studies related to a particular theme – this semester, revolutions. The goal of History 101 is to prepare our majors to succeed in more advanced seminars, including, eventually, a Capstone Seminar. History 101 will now consist of both a lecture which will meet twice a week for 75 minutes; and a recitation section which will meet for 75 minutes per week. Both components of the course are mandatory.    These changes will affect current history majors in the following way:       All students who have already taken the older form of the workshop (V57.0900) or Historical Studies: Theories and Practice will not have to take the new course. Their major requirements will not change at all.       Information about the new History 101 course:              History 101 is no longer a prerequisite for declaring the history major;   students are able to declare the major at their convenience and are encouraged to do so as early in their academic career as possible. History 101 is not restricted to juniors and seniors, as it was in years past. Students   who are interested in declaring history as a major must come to the history department- they should not declare the major from any other department. To declare a History major, you may turn in a major declaration form to the History Department (King Juan Carlos Center - 53 Washington Square South, Floor 4E). You may also submit the form via email to history.undergrad@nyu.edu .       History 101 will be offered every fall and spring semester.       History 101 is a prerequisite for the Capstone Seminar requirement.   Students cannot take the Capstone Seminar in the same semester that they   take History 101.       History 101 does not fulfill any geographical, Capstone Seminar or Pre-1800 requirements: it only fulfills the History 101 requirement for the major. History 101 does not count as an intro class in terms of requirements. Both components of the course are mandatory.       The remaining history requirements are unchanged.
